## Response Conventions

### Success Responses

| Method | Success Status | Body |
|--------|---------------|------|
| GET (single) | 200 | Resource object |
| GET (collection) | 200 | Paginated envelope (see below) |
| POST | 201 | Created resource object |
| PUT / PATCH | 200 | Updated resource object |
| DELETE | 204 | Empty body |

### Resource Object Shape

Every resource object includes an `id` field of type `string` (UUID) and `createdAt` / `updatedAt` timestamps in ISO 8601 format:

```json
{
  "id": "018e7b1a-4a2f-7000-8000-000000000001",
  "createdAt": "2024-03-15T10:30:00+00:00",
  "updatedAt": "2024-03-15T11:00:00+00:00"
}
```

{% if api_style == "api-platform" %}
API Platform uses `@id` (JSON-LD IRI) alongside `id`. The frontend uses the plain `id` field for routing and the TypeScript types reflect this.
{% endif %}

---

## Pagination Contract

All collection endpoints return a consistent pagination envelope:

```json
{
  "data": [ /* array of resource objects */ ],
  "meta": {
    "total": 120,
    "page": 1,
    "perPage": 20,
    "lastPage": 6
  },
  "links": {
    "first": "/api/users?page=1",
    "prev": null,
    "next": "/api/users?page=2",
    "last": "/api/users?page=6"
  }
}
```

### Pagination Query Parameters

| Parameter | Type | Default | Description |
|-----------|------|---------|-------------|
| `page` | integer | 1 | Current page (1-indexed) |
| `perPage` | integer | 20 | Items per page (max 100) |
| `sort` | string | `createdAt` | Sort field |
| `order` | `asc` / `desc` | `desc` | Sort direction |

Example: `GET /api/users?page=2&perPage=50&sort=email&order=asc`

The TypeScript type for the envelope is in `packages/shared-types`:

```typescript
export interface PaginatedResponse<T> {
  data: T[];
  meta: {
    total: number;
    page: number;
    perPage: number;
    lastPage: number;
  };
  links: {
    first: string | null;
    prev: string | null;
    next: string | null;
    last: string | null;
  };
}
```

